&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Professor [bold]Brice Dickson, [bold]Professor of International and Comparative Law, [bold]                                  [bold]Queen’s University Belfast (CRJ 16)[bold]&#xa0;[bold]‘The constitutional role of the judiciary if there were a codified Constitution: a view from Northern Ireland’
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]I have structure
[normal]d
[normal] my evidence in line with the terms of reference of the Committee’s inquiry.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]In Northern Ireland talk of a codified Constitution for the United Kingdom is likely to be divisive. Regardless of the content of any such codification, unionists will most probably see its very existence as a 
[normal]c
[normal]ement
[normal]ing 
[normal]of Northern Ireland’s current constitutional status, while nationalists will see it as an attempt to ignore th
[normal]e fact that 
[normal]Northern Ireland is 
[normal]materially 
[normal]different
[normal] from other regions of the UK
[normal]. During the recent debates on whether there should be a Bill
[normal] of Rights for the United Kingdom
[normal] (leading to the split report by the Commission 
[normal]on a Bill of Rights 
[normal]in December 2012)
[normal], many commentators of a nationalist disposition
[normal] in Northern Ireland
[normal] wanted nothing to do with the concept because they saw it as implying
[normal] a strengthening of ties between Great Britain and Northern Ireland. Even if 
[normal]a
[normal] codified Constitution were to say nothing more about the constitutional status of Northern Ireland than what is already stated in the Northern Ireland Act 1998 (which reflects t
[normal]he Belfast (Good Friday) Agreement
[normal])
[normal], it would be portrayed by the various political parties in different ways. Unionists tend to see the Belfast (Good Friday) Agreement as conclusive
[normal] – a 
[normal]destination. Nationalists tend to see it as transitional
[normal] – a 
[normal]step
[normal]ping
[normal] stone
[normal] to something better (for them).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It follows that if the judiciary in Northern Ireland were to be involved in interpreting 
[normal]a
[normal] codified Constitution 
[normal]the judges would be
[normal] 
[normal]almost 
[normal]bound to 
[normal]be accused of being
[normal] in some way politically biased.
[normal] This criticism 
[normal]has not been made in recent years because
[normal], although
[normal] the Northern Ireland Act 1998 is
[normal] already
[normal] a 
[normal]kind of 
[normal]constitution for Northern Ireland, it is 
[normal]nevertheless 
[normal]an ordinary Act of Parliament
[normal] and so
[normal] can be interpreted using a
[normal]ny of a number 
[normal]of tools for statutor
[normal]y interpretation 
[normal]currently 
[normal]available. 
[normal]J
[normal]udges have not been required to give the Act any ‘higher’ status. It is true that, on occasions, very senior judges, especially in the House of Lords or Supreme Court, have treated the 1998 Act as if it were indeed a 
[normal]const
[normal]i
[normal]tutional statute. But those comments must now be seen against the backdrop of decisions such as 
[normal]Watkins v 
[normal]Secretary of State for the 
[normal]Home 
[normal]Department
[normal] 
[normal][2006] UKHL 17, 
[normal]where
[normal] the House of Lords made it abundantly clear that there are no such things as constitutional rights and that drawing a line between constitutional statutes and ordinary statutes 
[normal]i
[normal]s a
[normal]n unnecessary
[normal] 
[normal]and 
[normal]perilous exercise. 
[normal]It is 
[normal]also 
[normal]true that the 
[normal]House of Lor
[normal]ds and 
[normal]Supreme Court ha
[normal]ve
[normal] been particularly respectful of the devolution Acts 
[normal]in
[normal] all three devolved regions 
[normal]of
[normal] the UK (see 
[normal]Robinson v Secretary of State for Northern Ireland
[normal] [2002] UKHL 32, 
[normal]AXA 
[normal]General Insurance Ltd 
[normal]v
[normal] Lord Advocate
[normal] [2011] UKSC 46,
[normal] 
[normal]and 
[normal]Atto
[normal]rney General v National Assembly for Wales Commission
[normal] [2012] UKSC 53), 
[normal]but
[normal] in a recent decision the 
[normal]Supreme Court did hold that the Scottish Parliament had acted outside its competence (see 
[normal]Salvesen v Riddell
[normal] [2013] UKSC 22).
[normal] 
[normal]   
[normal]      
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]I am not sure that any formal consultation would be necessary, given the need to respect the separ
[normal]ation of powers doctrine. It would be unwise for judges to comment on potential provisions in a codified Constitution because they might then have to recuse themselves at a later stage if the meaning of the provisions were to come before them (see 
[normal]Davidson
[normal] v Scottish Ministers
[normal] [2004] UKHL 34). The consultation that took place with the Law Lords when the establishment of the Supreme Court was proposed was more understandable, since the abolition of the Appellate Committee 
[normal]would have
[normal] significant consequences for the judges’
[normal] own
[normal] 
[normal]e
[normal]nvironment
[normal] and working methods
[normal]; even so, the split which emerged amongst their Lordships 
[normal]o
[normal]n th
[normal]at
[normal] matter was embarrassing and 
[normal]did nothing to enhance p
[normal]ublic confidence in the independence of the judiciary.
[normal] Askin
[normal]g judges in Northern Ireland to comment on a draft codified Constitution would be most unwise as it would inevitably involve them in issues that are even more politically sensitive in Northern Ireland than in Great Britain.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]I believe it would be sensible to limit the courts’ power to issuing a ‘declaration of incompatibility with the Constitution’. As with
[normal] declarations of incompatibility 
[normal]that can be 
[normal]issued a
[normal]lready
[normal] under section 4 of the Human Rights Act 1998, such a declaration 
[normal]w
[normal]ould not affect the validity of the piece of legislation in question nor alter the rights and duties of the parties to the litigation in which the matter arises. But there 
[normal]w
[normal]ould 
[normal]need to 
[normal]be some provision in the Constitution which requires a parliamentary a
[normal]nd/or governmental reaction to a judicial ‘declaration of incompatibility with the Constitution’
[normal] – something a bit more mandatory than section 10 of the Human Rights Act 1998
[normal]. Having a codified Constitution does not of itself require that a court be given 
[normal]the power to 
[normal]invalidate some law on the grounds of unconstitutionality. I think the model set by the Human Rights Act is ideal because it does not confer excessive power on judges, who 
[normal]have no electoral mandate
[normal], yet it imposes a
[normal]n
[normal] 
[normal](
[normal]albeit 
[normal]weak)
[normal] obligation o
[normal]n the government to do something to correct the 
[normal]incompatibility
[normal]. 
[normal]After the courts have issued a declaration of incompatibility with the Constitution o
[normal]ne option for the government would be to seek an amendment to the Constitution, through whatever mechanism
[normal]s are made available 
[normal]for that purpose
[normal] in the Constitution itself, so as to make the challenged law 
[normal]and the Constitution 
[normal]no longer incompatible.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Committee might usefully examine the experience of the Republic of Ireland in this context. A commonly 
[normal]held view there is that on occasions the Supreme Court has wielded too much power by declaring certain legislative provisions to be unconstitutional. If the judges
[normal] in Ireland
[normal] had had a lesser power (e.g. to declare merely an incompatibility)
[normal],
[normal] some undesira
[normal]ble political and financial consequences 
[normal]might
[normal] have been avoided. 
[normal]   
[normal] 
[normal]a) What would be the implications of these powers on existing constitutional doctrines, including parliamentary sovereignty and judicial review?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]As stated above, it is possible to have a system whereby judges can declare Acts of Parliament to be incompatible with the Constitution but not invalidate them. But to maintain the credibility of the Constitution in such a situation it would be important t
[normal]o have a provision in the Constitution mandating parliament and/or the government to react in a way which eliminates the incompatibility. It should be remembered that the Acts devolving power to the Scottish Parliament and to the Welsh and Northern Ireland
[normal] Assemblies make provision for courts to suspend the effect of a declaration of legislative incompetence to allow time for the devolved government to rectify the matter
[normal]. This was exercised for the first time in
[normal] 
[normal]Salvesen v Riddell
[normal] [2013] UKSC 22.
[normal] 
[normal]b) In th[bold]e context of question 3, what can we learn from the interaction between the UK courts and the European Court of Justice and European Court of Human Rights?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]I have made a detailed study of the interaction between the top UK court and the European Court of 
[normal]Human Rights (
[normal]Human Rights and the United Kingdom Supreme Court
[normal], OUP, 2013). I was able to demonstrate, I hope, that even today the top UK court and the Strasbourg Court are not always on the same wavelength – which is why a ‘dialogue’ between the courts i
[normal]s often useful. To date the Strasbourg Court has usually allowed member states a wide margin of appreciation as regards their internal constitutional arrangements (prisoner voting rights is an exception to this). Throughout the troubles in Northern Ireland
[normal] the European Court of Human Rights did not play a significant role in protecting human rights in Northern Ireland: it really only began to do so after the ceasefires were announced in 1994. The Strasbourg Court continues to defer rather meekly to national
[normal] governments when the latter decide that there is a public emergency threatening the life of the nation (see 
[normal]A v UK
[normal] (2009) 49 EHRR 29, the follow-up decision on the indefinite detention of foreign nationals in Belmarsh prison).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The nature of the jurisdict
[normal]ion of the Court of Justice of the EU (being mainly advisory, through ‘preliminary rulings’) is such that a codification of the UK’s Constitution ought not to make a significant difference. It is conceivable, though, that the 
[normal]Factortame
[normal]-type scenario – whe
[normal]re a UK court is allowed to ‘disapply’ an Act of Parliament because of its inconsistency with EU law – could cause serious difficulties if it were 
[normal]to arise in a context where the inconsistent provision was a provision in the Constitution. Given the anti-EU
[normal] sentiments which seem to abound in certain political circles within the UK at the moment, it is entirely possible that the codified Constitution will contain such inconsistent provisions. The document will have to make it abundantly clear how any such inc
[normal]onsistency is to be dealt with by the national judiciary. What the CJEU makes of the inconsistency is largely beyond the UK’s control. I do not think there is any particular Northern Irish dimension to this issue.  
[normal]      
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A priori
[normal] constitutional review is possible in Ireland and in France. On the 
[normal]whole, it has not worked particularly well
[normal] in either jurisdiction
[normal]. In Ireland the problem is that
[normal],
[normal] once a court has made a decision on the constitutionality of a Bill before it becomes an Act
[normal],
[normal] there can be no further challenge to the constitutionality of a
[normal]ny aspect of that Act after it has been passed (Article 
[normal]34.3.3 of the 1937 Constitution). In France 
[normal]a priori
[normal] review by the Conseil constitutionnel was deemed to be an inadequate mechanism by itself, so in 2010 the Conseil was given the power to conduct 
[normal]a 
[normal]posteriori
[normal] reviews as well. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In general, judges rightly shy away from considering 
[normal]t
[normal]he constitutionality of laws 
[normal]in abstracto
[normal]: they prefer to consider them in concrete cases. 
[normal]In Northern Ireland, since the Government of Ireland Act 1920, it has always been
[normal] possible to refer Bills to a court 
[normal]in order 
[normal]to check whether the devolved legislature has the competence to make that law (the court in question used to be the Judicial Committee of the Privy Council but since 
[normal]October 2009 it has been th
[normal]e Supreme Court).
[normal] 
[normal]References to the Privy Council during the days of the Stormont Parliament were 
[normal]very 
[normal]rare, and never led to a Bill being declared beyond th
[normal]at
[normal] Parliament’s competence. There has not yet been a reference to the Supreme Court
[normal] concerning a Bill before the Nort
[normal]hern Ireland Assembly
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Personally I am in favour of 
[normal]a priori
[normal] consideration of Bills being left to the political domain. The availability of judicial review at the 
[normal]a posteriori 
[normal]stage should be an adequate safeguard. If the point is made that the latter depends on some wealthy and/or courageous litigant bringing the matter to court, this can be answered by giving a power to some external actor – the Attorney General or the Human R
[normal]ights Commission perhaps – to bring the matter to court, much as the Northern Ireland Human Rights Commission 
[normal]has done
[normal] in relation to the inability of unmarried couples to apply to adopt children
[normal] (
[normal]Re NIHRC’s Application for Judicial Review
[normal] [2013] NICA 37)
[normal].
[normal]   
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In 
[normal]2004 I published a chapter in an edited collection in which I considered, but rejected, the idea that 
[normal]there should be a Constitutional Court for Northern Ireland (‘A Constitutional Court f
[normal]o
[normal]r Northern Ireland?’ in Andrew Le Sueur
[normal] (ed)
[normal], 
[normal]Building the UK’s New Supreme Court
[normal], OUP, 2004, 49-66
[normal]).
[normal] I hold the same view in relation to the idea of a Constitutional Co
[normal]urt for the United Kingdom. I support the view that the Supreme Court should be the final court for all legal matters in the United Kingdom, constitutional or otherwise. The fact that the Supreme Court is currently, in effect, the constitutional court as f
[normal]ar 
[normal]as 
[normal]the extent of dev
[normal]o
[normal]l
[normal]v
[normal]ed
[normal] powers are concerned is evidence of the fact that that court can consider constitutional issues just as effectively as any other body. Besides, the demarcation of labour issues that can arise whenever a country has more than on
[normal]e top court make it sensible to 
[normal]have
[normal] a more hierarchical structure. South Africa, France and Germany all suffer from 
[normal]demarcation issues
[normal] to some extent, although Germany less so on account of its clearer provisions on jurisdiction.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]If a separate Constituti
[normal]onal Court were to be created, the system for appointing its members would need to ensure that a view from Northern Ireland (and other devolve regions) is available to the Court.    
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]I addressed this precise issue during the course of my inaugural professorial lecture at 
[normal]Queen’s University in 2006 (
[normal]‘
[normal]The role of judges in the development of constitutions’ (2006) 57 Northern Ireland Legal Quarterly 332-351
[normal]; appended to this evidence
[normal]). At pages 337 to 344 I drew upon the experience of the US, France, Ireland, India, South Afr
[normal]ica and Canada to show what judges 
[normal]can 
[normal]do to support constitutionalism. I then made ten suggestions for how judges should reform the UK’s Constitution (pages 344 to 
[normal]351). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It must be remembered that the power of judges in the US to strike down Acts of Con
[normal]gress as unconstitutional was not conferred by the US Constitution but was grabbed by the Supreme Court in 
[normal]Marbury v Madison 
[normal](1803). What makes the power of the US Supreme Court somewhat frightening in this context – and the underlying reason, perhaps, why
[normal] the Court has been much criticised of late for being too activist – is the fact that amending the US Constitution is very difficult indeed to achieve, as the 
[normal]failure to obtain enough state ratifications for the Equal Rights Amendment in 1982 (guaranteeing
[normal] rights for women) clearly indicates. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]On the other hand, it is commonly acknowledged that the Supreme Court of India has been 
[normal]too
[normal] activist in recent years, usurping the powers of the Indian Parliament and in effect making laws that the judges have no rea
[normal]l expertise in devising. Australia, to my mind, is a good example of where the written Constitution of 1900 has had a deleterious effect on the judiciary: it has forced them to spend a lot of time trying to interpret language that is out of date and not ob
[normal]viously relevant to the 21st century. Some would say the same about the US Constitution, as evidenced by the US Supreme Court’s recent decision on the right to bear arms: 
[normal]District of Columbia v Heller
[normal] 554 US 570 (2008). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]If we are not to lead ou
[normal]r
[normal] judges down blind alleys and on wild goose chases we must ensure that any codified Constitution clearly sets out not just the powers of the judges but also the limits to those powers and the ways in which the
[normal] judges
[normal] should go about exercising them.    
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]  
[normal]January 2014
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]APPENDIX[bold]THE ROLE OF JUDGES [bold]IN THE DEVELOPMENT OF CONSTITUTIONS[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction[bold]The debate about the role of judges in the British constitution has been prolific and fierce in recent years. It has, though, tended to focus too much on history and not enough on possible futures. It has concentrated on the ‘is’ and 
[normal]not on the ‘ought’. And, like many debates, it has degenerated into one where there are basically two opposing camps, neither of which is prepared to give much ground to the other. There are a few outliers, but these too tend to squabble over their exact p
[normal]osition vis-à-vis the other protagonists rather than rising above the fray and adopting a more positive frame of mind. What is needed is a more holistic approach, one which recognises that there are advantages in both main positions, as well as in their va
[normal]riants, but which prefers to focus not on whether judges are more important than law-making politicians in maintaining constitutionalism but on what steps each of those élites should take to copper-fasten the constitution against the vicissitudes of 21
[normal]st
[normal] c
[normal]entury living. Judges in most other countries do play a crucial role in developing their national constitutions. Judges in the UK have, on the whole, underperformed in that area, at least in the last few decades. Now is the time for them to raise their gam
[normal]e. 
[normal]The article begins by summarising the current debate. It then proceeds to review some of the contributions made by judges to constitutions elsewhere than in the United Kingdom. In its final section it makes and tries to justify ten suggestions as to ho
[normal]w Britain’s top judges should reform the British constitution. Throughout, the article takes a broad approach to the term ‘constitution’. In particular it embraces within that term the rules and principles governing judicial freedom of action.    
[normal]The curr[bold]ent debate[bold]In March 2004 Adam Tomkins delivered his inaugural lecture as the Professor of Public Law at the University of Glasgow, a lecture which he later expanded into book form.
[normal] In this book he launched a passionate attack against those who advocate th
[normal]e theory known as ‘common law constitutionalism’ – the idea that at the core of the British constitutional order lies the common law made by judges. Tomkins belittled the views of commentators such as Jeffrey Jowell and Dawn Oliver at University College Lo
[normal]ndon and Paul Craig at Oxford. He had the temerity to undermine that guru of the common law, Ronald Dworkin.
[normal] And he had a go, too, at Sir John Laws, the Court of Appeal judge who has extolled the virtues of the common law in extra-judicial writings
[normal] as we
[normal]ll as in his own judgments.
[normal] Particular opprobrium, however, 
[normal]was reserved for Trevor Allan at Cambridge.
[normal] Tomkins described Allan as a ‘hardliner’ and labelled the breadth of his support for constitutional justice as ‘staggering’. To Allan, said Tomkins, ‘it seems that there is no constitutional problem that is incapable of being solved by the courts and [tha
[normal]t] no constitutional problem is solved until it is solved by the courts’. Tomkins thought this was ‘legal constitutionalism at its most extreme’.
[normal] 
[normal]Instead of relying upon the courts as the guardians of the constitution, Tomkins promotes the notion of 
[normal]‘political accountability’. Prior to acquiring his chair he had written articles defending what he called ‘the political constitution’,
[normal] a throwback to the phrase used by John Griffith in the 1970s.
[normal] In such works Tomkins has to some extent been following 
[normal]the lead given by Martin Loughlin at the London School of Economics and Political Science, in three books published since 1992.
[normal] The reliance placed by Tomkins and Loughlin on the essentially political nature of the constitution  is not so very far removed
[normal] from the views of those who, like Christopher Forsyth and Mark Elliott at Cambridge,
[normal] still maintain the rather Diceyean line that all judicial development of the law must ultimately be traced back to the supposed intention of Parliament. Tomkins’ approac
[normal]h has to some extent been bolstered by the likes of Thomas Poole, who claims that common law constitutionalism fails to adequately explain the main features of the way judicial review actually operates in Britain.
[normal] Poole sees judges as aristocrats and mora
[normal]l imperialists.
[normal] Another lawyer at Glasgow, Gavin Anderson, makes three further criticisms of common law constitutionalism (or, rather, of what he calls ‘rights constitutionalism’): he believes that it fails to control private, as opposed to public, power;
[normal] it 
[normal]ignores the significance of the practices and actors of the global economy; and it considerably overstates the capacity of judges to be coherently instrumental.
[normal] In Anderson’s words, ‘judges, like other law-creating subjects, construct distinctive pers
[normal]onal accounts of the legal world, whose mutual interaction necessarily leads to inconsistency and contradiction’.
[normal] 
[normal]Not surprisingly, well-known attempts have been made to pigeon-hole those who write in this area by giving them fancy labels. Martin Loughli
[normal]n describes people who place great emphasis on the work of the courts as ‘conservative normativists’; those who prefer to place their trust in Parliament and in politics, Loughlin calls ‘functionalists’.
[normal] He reserves a third label for people who believe th
[normal]at courts should not have the final say over everything but should at least articulate principles which can guide the executive in the exercise of its discretions. This category should, I think, embrace people like Sir William Wade (that much-lamented icon
[normal] of British constitutional law who died in 2005
[normal]), Robert Stevens (still writing about British judges 50 years after his first article was published
[normal]) and Sir Neil MacCormick, the eminent legal philosopher at Edinburgh whose latest book, 
[normal]Rhetoric and the R
[normal]ule of Law
[normal], provides many insights into the nature of judicial reasoning. These people, in Loughlin’s terms, are ‘liberal normativists’. If, like me, you have an in-built aversion to such grandiose labels you might prefer the much more prosaic categories s
[normal]uggested by Carol Harlow and Richard Rawlings, who simply talk of red-light and green-light approaches.
[normal]My own approach lies somewhere between red and amber. In Loughlin’s terms I’d be a ‘liberal-conservative normativist’. This means that, in my view, jud
[normal]ges can and should play a very significant role in shaping constitutions. They should actively seek to control both the government and Parliament, preventing those institutions from damaging the rule of law and the separation of powers. There should be ver
[normal]y few issues which are non-justiciable. At the same time, the power of judges should not be unbridled. The judiciary should be just one site in which sovereignty is located. Power must also reside in other sites,
[normal] and values other than legal ones must be p
[normal]romoted. But judges bring relative detachment, valuable experience and absolute integrity to their work. We should, therefore, give them a fairly free rein.
[normal] We should not, I think, adopt the approach of Horace Walpole, who in 1770 wrote in a letter: ‘Ever
[normal]ybody talks of the constitution, but all sides forget that the constitution actually works 
[normal]extremely well, if they would let it alone’.
[normal] Letting it alone should not be considered an option today.
[normal] 
[normal]In any event, the critics of common law constitutionalism 
[normal]tend to ignore some important ‘modern’ features of the British legal system. For a start, they do not generally respect the influence of European institutions. Anyone wishing to remind themselves of that influence should consult the writings of Nicholas Ba
[normal]mforth.
[normal] He brings a dose of realism to the debate by observing that no theory about today’s UK constitution can be valid unless it explains why a British court will ‘disapply’ an Act of Parliament if it is inconsistent with EC law or why, as a result of t
[normal]he Human Rights Act, courts are free to disagree with Parliament – not just with government – that a piece of primary legislation is compatible with the European Convention on Human Rights. Bamforth endorses what Gordon Anthony usefully describes as the ‘s
[normal]pill-over’ effect – the idea that courts in the UK are influenced by European considerations even though the specific matter at issue is not regulated by EC law or the Convention.
[normal] The main message coming from Bamforth’s and Anthony’s analyses, with which 
[normal]I agree, is that reports of the death of common law constitutionalism are greatly exaggerated. 
[normal]And if such reports were exaggerated three or four years ago, they are even more so today because in the last few years there has been a renaissance of interest
[normal] in the rule of law on the part of our top judges, the Law Lords. Those judges are, of course, about to metamorphose into Justices of the UK’s Supreme Court,
[normal] although not, it seems, before October 2009.
[normal] When that occurs, their role as guardians of our co
[normal]nstitution will surely become even more obvious.
[normal] As it is, Law Lords are already standing their ground against New Labour’s increasing authoritarianism.
[normal] Their two recent decisions on the position of foreign detainees at Belmarsh prison are, it is to be h
[normal]oped, not just straws in the wind but emblems of a whole new spirit of judicial activism.
[normal] At the end of 2004 eight Law Lords ruled that internment 
[normal]without trial under the Anti-terrorism, Crime and Security Act 2001 was contrary to the European Convention’
[normal]s guarantee of the right not to be deprived of liberty on a discriminatory or disproportionate basis.
[normal] They measured the Act against Article 15 of the Convention, which is not one of the articles incorporated by the Human Rights Act, so this is a further e
[normal]xample of Anthony’s ‘spill-over’ effect. A year later a unanimous bench of seven Law Lords ruled that no British court can rely upon evidence that may have been obtained anywhere in the world through the use of torture.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A close reading of the judgments 
[normal]in both those cases could surely leave no-one in any doubt that the highest court in the land plays an absolutely crucial role not just in protecting human rights but in curbing the excesses of Parliament and the executive. Yet in his comments on the first
[normal] of these decisions, Adam Tomkins damns with faint praise.
[normal] He claims that the Law Lords were ‘merely following a path already broken by others’ and that ‘the change of tone…should not mislead us into thinking that it heralds a change of approach’. His jus
[normal]tification for this view is that after the judgments were issued the Belmarsh detainees were still in prison and the rest of the Anti-terrorism Act was still on the statute book. He seems to be saying that unless judges can completely usurp the functions o
[normal]f elected politicians they are entirely useless. To adapt his own phrase, this is surely republicanism at its most extreme. 
[normal]To appreciate better the contribution judges could and should make to the UK’s constitution one needs to look abroad.
[normal] The next sec
[normal]tion of this article will conduct a brief survey of some leading liberal democracies to see what innovations could possible be mirrored in Britain. 
[normal]Contributions to constitutionalism made by judges elsewhere[bold] 
[normal]The American Constitution, one often reads, is
[normal] be applauded for the way it permits the Supreme Court to invalidate Acts of Congress if they are ‘unconstitutional’. But of course that power was not conferred by the 1787 document signed by George Washington and others, nor by the first 10 amendments whi
[normal]ch were agreed in 1791 and which we call the Bill of Rights. Instead, the power was created 
[normal]for itself
[normal] by the US Supreme Court. In 
[normal]Marbury v Madison
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]in 1803, Chief Justice Marshall skilfully gave President Jefferson the result he was 
[normal]hoping for by holdin
[normal]g that the attempt by the previous President, John Adams, to appoint a number of federal judges before he left office, was ineffective. This was because the Act of Congress
[normal] authorising the Court to enforce the appointments was held not to be valid. Under 
[normal]Article III of the Constitution the Court had been given a number of specific functions and without express authorisation Congress had tried to expand those functions. Very cleverly the Court denied to itself the lesser power to enforce judicial appointmen
[normal]ts but in the very act of doing so conferred on itself the much greater power to declare Acts of Congress to be unconstitutional.
[normal]It is on this slender foundation the whole edifice of judicial review in America has subsequently been constructed, although i
[normal]nstances of Acts being declared unconstitutional remain rare. It did occur when Franklin Roosevelt was pursuing his New Deal ideology in the 1930s, and the Supreme Court’s stance on that occasion is sometimes taken, wrongly I think, as an illustration of j
[normal]udicial opposition in America to the notion of social and economic rights.
[normal] The truth is that the New Deal case turned on a different point altogether, namely on whether Congress had delegated too much power to an administrative agency without giving it ad
[normal]equate guidance on how to exercise that power. If anything, therefore, the decision was a blow in favour of constitutionalism and a few years later the Supreme Court had little difficulty in upholding different New Deal legislation which was more clearly d
[normal]rafted.
[normal]But it is worth noting that in recent years considerable scepticism has been voiced in America about the current Supreme Court’s commitment to constitutionalism. Disdain for judges’ constitutional work has been displayed, for example, by Mark Tush
[normal]net of Georgetown Law School, in books with provocative titles such as 
[normal]The New Constitutional Order 
[normal]and 
[normal]Taking the Constitution Away from the Courts
[normal], where he argues that the credit usually accorded to the US Supreme Court for maintaining the rule of law 
[normal]is grossly overestimated. Others have taken up the same theme. Robert Bork, whose nomination to the Supreme Court by President Reagan was vetoed by the Senate in 1987, recently published a book condemning what he calls ‘the world-wide rule of judges’.
[normal] Mar
[normal]k Levin, likewise, has written a study entitled 
[normal]Men in Black: How the Supreme Court is Destroying America
[normal]. And Jeremy Waldron, a New Zealander now based in New York, maintains the same line.
[normal] Some legal academics are less sweeping in their condemnation, bu
[normal]t in the lead-up to the not unexpected death of Chief Justice Rehnquist in 2005, and in the commentaries on the appointment of John Roberts as his successor, there have been numerous negative assessments of how little the US Supreme Court has contributed t
[normal]o constitutionalism in recent times.
[normal] Its somewhat half-hearted efforts to control the American government’s excesses during the current ‘war on terror’ are, to many, 
[normal]symptomatic of the malaise.
[normal] If the UK’s judges are failing to rise to constitutional cha
[normal]llenges, it seems that American judges, despite having a much greater tradition in the field, and more ‘weapons’ at their disposal, are also in need of strong encouragement to be more active.           
[normal]In America the review of the constitutionality of pri
[normal]mary legislation can occur only 
[normal]after
[normal] it has been enacted. In France it can occur only 
[normal]beforehand
[normal]. The Constitution of the Fifth Republic, in place since 1958, created a body known as the Constitutional Council (
[normal]Le Conseil constitutionnel
[normal]).
[normal] This body is n
[normal]ot actually a court at all and its nine members are not judges, but one of its functions is to examine draft statutes (
[normal]lois
[normal]) to see if they conform with the Constitution. The Councillors do not read or listen to arguments put by advocates for the opposing 
[normal]points of view. They do their own thinking, taking account only of documents preceding the draft law and of the French Constitution itself. But they have been adept at reading into that Constitution additional criteria for assessing whether laws are in con
[normal]formity with it. 
[normal]The turning point came in 1971. A year earlier the French Cabinet had ordered the dissolution of a small left-wing political party, 
[normal]La Gauche Prolétarienne
[normal]. In response to this, activists such as Jean-Paul Sartre and Simone de Beauvoir se
[normal]t up another group named after the newspaper of the banned party, 
[normal]La Cause du Peuple
[normal]. The government directed the local prefect not to register this new group but a local administrative court rather bravely ruled that the prefect had no such power to refus
[normal]e registration. The government then introduced a Bill to widen the prefect’s powers and it was this Bill which the Constitutional Council struck down. It did so by implying into the Constitution the so-called ‘fundamental principles recognised by the laws 
[normal]of the Republic’, a phrase mentioned in the Preamble to the 1946 Constitution of the Fourth French Republic and deemed to be affirmed by the Preamble to the 1958 Constitution.
[normal] One of these principles, said the Council, was that of freedom of association. 
[normal]And it is on the back of that momentous decision that the Constitutional Council has since built an envious reputation for guaranteeing civil liberties in France. Last year the Council pronounced on 18 draft laws. This year it has already invalidated parts
[normal] of the proposed anti-terrorism law,
[normal] although it upheld the controversial youth employment law, which was found not to be in breach of the principle of equality.
[normal] Of course, political and popular pressure later conspired to force President Chirac to suspe
[normal]nd that law, a move which prompted a recent commentator to suggest that the ritual of mass protests reversing 
[normal]unpopular governmental measures should actually be regarded as an informal part of the French constitution.
[normal] 
[normal]The French Council has another impor
[normal]tant function – the supervision of elections. That responsibility also fell to the US Supreme Court when Al Gore challenged the electoral victory of George W Bush in 2000. The Court split 5 to 4 in favour of not permitting any further recounting of the vot
[normal]es in Florida, thereby handing the presidency to Mr Bush.
[normal] Analysts usually observe that there was an uncanny alignment between the supposed political views of the nine US justices and the ultimate outcome of the case, but whether any of the judges actuall
[normal]y allowed their personal political predilections to influence their voting is impossible to verify. Their political predilections could have been the 
[normal]result
[normal] of, rather than the 
[normal]cause
[normal] of, their conception of the role of judges in developing the constitution
[normal]. Adam Tomkins would probably condemn this case as another lamentable example of unhelpful judicial interference in constitutional affairs, but if so he would also have to condemn the involvement of the highest civil court in Italy
[normal] when, earlier this year
[normal], it confirmed the electoral victory of Romano Prodi. As we know from the experience of Germany last year and Iraq this year, courts may not be able to force politicians into coalitions, but they can at least determine who won most votes at an election. If
[normal] a top court is not the right body to decide that, who is?  And, by the way, according to opinion polls, the reputation of the American Supreme Court hardly suffered at all as a result of its intervention in 
[normal]Bush v Gore
[normal].
[normal]The American Court has also been a
[normal]ctive in developing ‘unenumerated’ constitutional rights – rights which are not expressly mentioned in the Constitution, but which judges see as implicit. But we do not need to cross the Atlantic, or even the English Channel, to encounter judges who are pr
[normal]epared to invent such rights. Just down the road is a jurisdiction where the Supreme Court has been remarkably active in doing just that.  Ireland even allows its judges to assess the constitutionality of legislation 
[normal]either before or after
[normal] its enactment.
[normal] 
[normal]One of the unenumerated rights in Ireland is the right to privacy. The others include the right to strike, the right to earn a living, the right to communicate, the right to access the courts, the right to 
[normal]be legally represented if facing criminal charges,
[normal] the right to protection of one’s health, the right to travel, the right to found a family and the right to know the identity of one’s natural mother. All of these rights are creations of the common law.
[normal] Not everyone is a fan of how the Irish judges have 
[normal]gone about their task – David Gwynn Morgan at Cork (I think he goes with full title, i.e. David Gwynn Morgan), for example, is critical of their inconsistency and of their reliance on principles which to him are not rational.
[normal] Furthermore, in the last few 
[normal]years a marked conservatism has become evident within the Irish Supreme Court.
[normal] Worrying examples are the case of Jamie Sinnott, a young autistic man who was, in effect, denied the right to education,
[normal] and the case of 
[normal]TD
[normal],
[normal] where only one judge, Mrs Justice
[normal] Denham, was bold enough to order the government to provide support units for teenagers with behavioural difficulties – the other judges saw that as a step too far for the judiciary, a step that would breach the doctrine of separation of powers by allowing
[normal] judges to do what was supposedly the preserve of Dáil Éireann.  
[normal]In this respect the Irish Supreme Court has not followed the lead of the Supreme Court of India, which has come under attack not for being judicially 
[normal]inactive
[normal] but for being judicially 
[normal]over-a
[normal]ctive
[normal]. It has been particularly imaginative in developing the right to life and personal liberty, which is guaranteed by Article 21 of the Indian Constitution of 1950 but which, thanks to the Supreme Court, now embraces as well the right to shelter, the ri
[normal]ght to health, the right to work, the right to clean air and clean water and the right to information. In a recent case brought by a journalist, the Indian Supreme Court relied on the right to equality in Article 14 of the Constitution to order criminal ju
[normal]stice agencies to investigate the alleged financing of terrorist organisations by high-ranking politicians.
[normal] This prompted one critic to remark that what was formerly judicial activism had evolved into judicial arrogance
[normal] and he warned that unless the Supr
[normal]eme Court exercises restraint, ‘the activist profile may be the first footprints of an impending constitutional lawlessness in India’.
[normal]       
[normal]Well, maybe the Indian court 
[normal]has
[normal] gone too far, and maybe the Irish court 
[normal]is
[normal] wise to be cautious. But in the UK ju
[normal]dges are a long way from reaching those outer limits of constitutional activism. And they have far to go before coming anywhere near the role played by the Constitutional Court of South Africa or, in recent years, by the Supreme Court of Canada, although t
[normal]hose courts do benefit from having very modern constitutional documents from which to work. It was apparent from its earliest judgments in the mid-1990s
[normal] that the 
[normal]South African Court was going to be one which grounded its decisions in a purposive interpret
[normal]ation of the country’s Constitution, which came to its conclusions only after considering how courts in other parts of the world – and not just courts based on the Anglo-Saxon model – had resolved similar issues, and which contained judges who couched thei
[normal]r judgments not in vapid legal jargon but in inspirational phrases.
[normal] The Court has also been refreshingly pragmatic, best illustrated perhaps in its use of the power to suspend the invalidation of legislation until the government has had a reasonable time 
[normal]to amend it.
[normal] This is a power which the Federal Constitutional Court of Germany has also conferred upon itself.
[normal] And the South African Court has pronounced at length on the scope of social and economic rights, yet without usurping the mandate of elected po
[normal]liticians in that domain.
[normal] 
[normal]Canada, too, has benefited from having a Supreme Court that is imaginative and internationalist in its outlook, although in the view of one commentator, there is ‘no set of judges in the developed world who are treated by the 
[normal]general population with such glowering suspicion’.
[normal] My colleague Rory O’Connell has made a special study of the ‘political’ role of the court
[normal] and is currently analysing how it has innovatively developed the concept of equality. The leading Canadian schola
[normal]r in this field, Kent Roach, has shown in his book 
[normal]The Supreme Court on Trial
[normal], that ‘an independent and courageous judiciary is the best institution we have to remind us of’ the effects of our actions on the unpopular and the disadvantaged.
[normal] One of the num
[normal]erous decisions Roach highlights
[normal] is that here the Supreme Court read into the human rights code of Alberta the right not be discriminated against on the basis of sexual orientation, even though the legislature had deliberately omitted that right.
[normal]  
[normal]So, a
[normal]ll over the world top courts have deployed considerable imagination in developing their national constitutions. And frequently they have achieved this without relying upon the specific wording of their constitution. New Zealand, like Britain, does not have
[normal] a written constitution, but that has not stopped the highest court there from ruling that people should be compensated if their fundamental human rights are breached.
[normal] It is worth remembering, too, that 
[normal]international
[normal] courts play an ever more important rol
[normal]e in promoting constitutionalism. Some would say that the European Court of Justice, like the Indian Supreme Court, has been a little 
[normal]too
[normal] enthusiastic in doing just that.
[normal] Steven Greer, at Bristol, argues that the European Court of Human Rights has devised
[normal] both primary and secondary constitutional principles to guide its own adjudication processes.
[normal] Certainly that Court has judged important constitutional issues arising within Britain. It has ruled that it is not contrary to basic democratic principles to a
[normal]llow members of Parliament to be immune from being sued for whatever they say in Parliament.
[normal] It has also insisted, in a case that came from Guernsey, that judicial power must be wielded completely separately from executive or legislative power,
[normal] a decisio
[normal]n which prompted the British Lord Chancellor to announce that he would no longer sit as a judge. And in what seems to me a less impressive decision, the European Court upheld the quaint rule that no-one can sit in the British Parliament unless he or she is
[normal] prepared to swear 
[normal]personal
[normal] allegiance to the Queen.
[normal] That, surely, must be an aberration? 
[normal]Suggestions for how judges should reform the UK constitution[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]So courts elsewhere have managed to develop constitutions quite significantly. This final section of t
[normal]he article makes a number of suggestions as to how UK judges should amend the British constitution – without the need for Parliamentary or governmental approval. These changes would create a more ‘constitutionalised’ state, meaning that the distribution an
[normal]d 
[normal]exercise of power would be controlled in a more consistent and principled fashion and that people would be left with a greater sense of being citizens of the world rather than of one small corner of it, Within the last century British judges have been un
[normal]necessarily timid in the constitutional field.
[normal] The time has come for them to be more assertive.
[normal] 
[normal]First, British judges should resurrect and develop the concept of ‘constitutional rights’. A few judges did flirt with this idea in pre-Human Rights Act days
[normal], in cases like 
[normal]Leech
[normal], 
[normal]Witham
[normal] and 
[normal]Simms
[normal].
[normal] Now that that Act has embedded most of the Convention rights in our domestic law the time seems to me to be riper than ever for the enunciation of rights unenumerated in that Act. Such a position is supported by at
[normal] least two former Law Lords,
[normal] and also by the Cambridge scholar Mark Elliott.
[normal] Unfortunately, as I tried to indicate in the memorial lecture for Stephen Livingstone earlier this year,
[normal] Britain’s Law Lords have been unwilling to go beyond Convention rights 
[normal]by affirming the existence of additional rights under the common law. In particular they failed to do so in the Northern Irish case of 
[normal]Cullen
[normal],
[normal] where a person held in custody was, in defiance of the rules, denied access to a solicitor at certain times. By 
[normal]3 to 2 (with Lords Bingham and Steyn dissenting) the Lords refused to award any compensation for this breach of rights. Very regrettably, just a month ago the House set its face more firmly than ever against the idea of developing the concept of constituti
[normal]onal rights: in 
[normal]Watkins v Home Office
[normal] 
[normal]they held that if prison officers maliciously interfere with a prisoner’s correspondence with his solicitor, they will not be liable to pay compensation if no actual loss has been suffered by the prisoner. Lord Bingha
[normal]m seemed to go back on what he 
[normal]said in 
[normal]Cullen
[normal] and joined Lord Rodger in claiming that the fact that the Human Rights Act was now in force was a further reason for 
[normal]not
[normal] developing the concept of constitutional rights. With respect, I think that is misguided.
[normal] There is surely much more to rights under the constitution than the concept of human rights? In my view the three key constitutional rights which judges should immediately develop and provide compensation for if breached are the right to access to justic
[normal]e,
[normal] the right to equality
[normal] and the right to fairness in decision-making.
[normal]     
[normal]My second suggested reform is that judges should develop the idea of positive state duties as the corollary of constitutional rights. They should steal a march on their Strasbou
[normal]rg colleagues in this regard, for the latter have been a bit hesitant in fashioning duties out of Articles in the European Convention.
[normal] To some extent British judges have already developed positive duties based on Article 2,
[normal] but there is a lot more they c
[normal]ould do vis-à-vis, say, Articles 3 and 8. For instance, if women have the right not to be subjected to domestic violence, should the state not be under a duty to provide refuges and other support facilities for abused women? And if we all have the right to
[normal] be free from degrading treatment and personally secure, should judges not oblige the state to protect us against environmental degradation? The Indian Supreme Court has been severely criticised for inappropriate meddling in environmental issues,
[normal] but in B
[normal]ritain the courts have been almost completely silent in the area. 
[normal] Thirdly, judges should assert more forcefully their power to review the exercise of Crown prerogatives. There is no need to follow Tomkins in calling for a Prerogative (Abolition) Act.
[normal] Th
[normal]e decision in the 
[normal]GCHQ
[normal] case, back in 1984,
[normal] was clearly a missed opportunity to subject the government more meaningfully to the rule of law. Although the European Court of Human Rights agreed that considerations of national security justified the British g
[normal]overnment’s ban on trade unions at the site in question,
[normal] the House of Lords could surely have been more interventionist in assessing the strength of the government’s claim. True, 
[normal]later cases have shown that the courts are sometimes willing to intervene on other prerogative powers, such as the power to issue pas
[normal]sports,
[normal] to grant pardons
[normal] or to to render diplomatic assistance to a British subject who is suffering violation of a fundamental human right as the result of the conduct of the authorities of a foreign state.
[normal] Given recent controversies over peerages for 
[normal]donors of money, maybe judges will soon get the opportunity to decide whether certain honours have been legally bestowed. And it is not inconceivable that the lawfulness of resort to foreign military action will soon or later be justiciable, whether or not
[normal] Parliamentary approval is also required.
[normal]  But Britain still awaits its equivalent to the Watergate case in America.
[normal] There the Supreme Court recognised that the President does have the right to keep many conversations confidential, but it nevertheless he
[normal]ld that the duty to ensure fairness in a criminal trial overrides that privilege. Richard Nixon resigned as President two weeks after the Supreme Court’s decision.
[normal] The closest Britain has come to this degree of scrutiny of executive privilege was probably
[normal] during the recent Hutton Inquiry into the death of David Kelly.
[normal] The outcome of that inquiry is for present purposes irrelevant, but what 
[normal]is
[normal] worth noting is the irony that a Law Lord who was not presiding in a court and who could not make any judgment as 
[normal]to civil or criminal liability was nevertheless supplied with more information than he would have been given if he had been so presiding – he even got to see Alastair Campbell’s private diary! 
[normal]My fourth suggestion is that the doctrine which allows foreign
[normal] governments to claim sovereign immunity when sued in the United Kingdom needs to be restricted. The primacy of customary international law should be recognised. For example, people who are the victims of state-sponsored torture abroad should be able to su
[normal]e the foreign governments in British courts
[normal] and, if they win, they should be able to enforce the judgment against the foreign government’s assets in this country. As it happens, an appeal dealing with this point has just concluded in the House of Lords.
[normal] 
[normal]When they are writing their judgments let’s hope the Law Lords in that case make as good a use of international law as they did in the two Belmarsh cases
[normal] and in the Pinochet case some years ago.
[normal]  
[normal]Fifthly, as I argued in the Livingstone lecture,
[normal] judges 
[normal]should put a severe dent in the constitutional principle that international treaties ratified by the government have no effect 
[normal]within our national legal system unless they have been expressly incorporated into our law.
[normal] In the Northern Irish case of 
[normal]McKerr
[normal] case, two years ago,
[normal] Lord Steyn called for this dualist approach to international law to be reconsidered. A majority of judges in the High Court of Australia came to the same conclusion nearly 10 years before that,
[normal] though it is fair to say that the idea
[normal] has not since taken root there and, apart from its work on the rights of indigenous peoples,
[normal] the Australian Court has a record that is probably worse than that of the House of Lords in implying constitutional rights.
[normal] Of course allowing treaties to have 
[normal]an 
[normal]effect 
[normal]does not mean that they have to become 
[normal]binding
[normal]: judges should develop a rebuttable presumption that national law 
[normal]must 
[normal]be read in a way which makes it consistent with ratified treaties unless there are very strong policy reasons why an inconsisten
[normal]cy should be preserved. This would go further than the principle of statutory construction which is currently applied, namely, that statutes are to be read as consistent with ratified treaties only if they are reasonably capable of bearing such a meaning.
[normal]Sixthly, judges should expand still further the sources they are prepared to look at before they decide cases. At present they very largely restrict themselves to ‘legal’ sources, ignoring information which is primarily economic or sociological in nature.
[normal] They should, in short, accept American-style ‘Brandeis briefs’.
[normal] Provided limits are placed on the size of such documents, and that resort to oral argument is more time-limited, as it is in the Washington and Strasbourg courts, there is no reason to belie
[normal]ve that proceedings in British courts would be unduly lengthened as a result of this reform.   
[normal]Seventhly, and this links to the point just made, judges need to commit themselves to a much more contextual approach to statutory interpretation, one that goes
[normal] beyond the requirement in section 3 of the Human Rights Act 1998 that legislation must be read and given effect in a way which is compatible with Convention rights ‘so far as it is possible to do so’.
[normal] An archetypal example of this 
[normal]not
[normal] happening is the re
[normal]cent case of 
[normal]R v J
[normal],
[normal] where a man in his thirties who had allegedly had repeated sex with a 13-year-old girl was charged with indecent assault on a woman, contrary to section 14 of the Sexual Offences Act 1956. He was not charged with having unlawful interc
[normal]ourse with a girl under 16, contrary to section 6, because a prosecution for that offence had to be brought within 12 months and this one had not 
[normal]been.
[normal] The four male Law Lords allowed the defendant’s appeal against conviction, on the basis that Parliament
[normal] could have had no possible purpose in prohibiting a prosecution under section 6 after the lapse of 12 months if exactly the same conduct could then be prosecuted under section 14.
[normal] Lord Bingham said that any other result was ‘impossible’ and Lord Steyn th
[normal]ought the conclusion was ‘inescapable’. Yet Lady Hale, who is so far the only woman to have been appointed to our top court, strongly dissented. For her the only unfairness in the case was that being done by her fellow judges to the young girl and the many
[normal] like her.
[normal] Lady Hale said the Sexual Offences Act was a mess when it was enacted and was an ever greater mess when it was amended. It simply was not possible to discern within it a Parliamentary intention along the lines suggested by her brethren. As she 
[normal]put it: ‘Although we do have to try to make sense of the words Parliament has used, we do not have to supply Parliament with the thinking that it never did and the words that it never used.’
[normal] I fervently hope that Lady Hale’s approach to statutory interpre
[normal]tation is the one that begins to prevail. As we all know, context is everything.
[normal]My eighth point is that senior judges should begin to exercise the power to overrule precedents for the future only. At present, when they overrule a precedent, one of the par
[normal]ties to the case at hand bears the consequences of the change to the law, even though that party might have thought the ‘old’ law was perfectly good and had based his or her conduct on it. Prospective overruling avoids this sense of injustice, allowing the
[normal] case at hand to be decided in accordance with the pre-existing law but sending out a message to future litigants that for them the law has changed. The Federal Constitutional Court of Germany has given itself this power, where practical reasons demand it.
[normal] Seven Law Lords asserted it for themselves in the 
[normal]Spectrum Plus 
[normal]case last year, but they opted not to make use of it on the facts before them.
[normal] There seems to me to be particular scope for prospective overruling in criminal cases, where it is surely unju
[normal]st that a defendant can find him- or herself punished for falling foul of a new interpretation of the law that did not exist at the time the alleged crime was committed.
[normal]Ninthly, judges should be prepared to consider abstract legal questions, the so-calle
[normal]d 
[normal]actio popularis
[normal]. They are edging towards doing this, as is evident from cases such as the one taken by 
[normal]The Guardian
[normal] against the statutory ban on campaigning to abolish the monarchy
[normal] or the 
[normal]one brought by the Family Planning Association here in Belfast ag
[normal]ainst the uncertainty inherent in our abortion laws.
[normal] If judges did a lot more of this kind of judging they would help to clarify legal principles and in the process greatly enhance the rule of law. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Finally, and most radically, our top judges should 
[normal]claim for themselves the power to declare Acts of Parliament to be unconstitutional. We should never forget that the doctrine of Parliamentary sovereignty, which supposedly lies at the base of our constitution, is itself a construct of the common law.
[normal] The
[normal] current Attorney General, Lord Goldsmith, expressly stated this in an answer to a Parliamentary question asked by Lord Lester of Herne Hill two years ago.
[normal] Judges can therefore, if so inclined, modify the doctrine. This is what the Law Lords were invited 
[normal]to do last year when there was a challenge by the Countryside Alliance to the constitutionality of the Hunting Act 2004, passed by the House of Commons without the consent of the second Chamber.
[normal] While all nine Law Lords held the Act to be valid, because i
[normal]t was passed in accordance with the Parliament Act of 1949, which in turn had been passed in accordance with the Parliament Act of 1911, five Law Lords expressly stated
[normal] that if the House of Commons alone were to try to delete from the 1911 Act the section
[normal] which prevents it from extending the maximum permitted life of a Parliament beyond five years, that would 
[normal]not
[normal] be a constitutional Act. Lord Steyn went further, suggesting that courts should be able to invalidate Acts which seek to abolish any fundamental 
[normal]feature of our constitution, such as the right of access to judicial review.
[normal] 
[normal]In 2004, when the government was pushing another of its Asylum and Immigration Bills through Parliament, it inserted a provision
[normal] which would have ousted the jurisdiction of the
[normal] courts to hear challenges against decisions of the immigration appeal tribunals. There was a huge outcry, not least from Lord Woolf, the Lord Chief Justice.
[normal] Eventually the clause was dropped. But if Parliament had gone ahead and enacted it, would courts 
[normal]have held it to be unconstitutional? I very much hope so. Similarly, if in April 2006 the government had not climbed down on its Legislative and Regulatory Reform Bill, under which ministers could have done all sorts of things that only an elected Parliame
[normal]nt should be able to do, I like to 
[normal]think that, had a challenge been raised in the courts against a government measure taken under the Act, judges would have declared it too to be unconstitutional. As Gibbon noted in 
[normal]The Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire
[normal], published around the same time as the American Constitution: ‘The principles of a free constitution are irrecoverably lost, when the legislative power is nominated by the executive’.
[normal] Or, as the US Supreme Court put it in 1966, ‘Where rights secured by t
[normal]he Constitution are involved, there can be no rule making or legislation which would abrogate them’.
[normal]  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]* Professor of International and Comparat
[normal]ive Law, Queen’s University Belfast. This is a version of my inaugural lecture, which was delivered under the same title at Queen’s University Belfast on 27 April 2006. Although the overall thrust and main recommendations of the lecture have been maintaine
[normal]d, there has been some slight restructuring and alteration of details. I am very grateful for comments made on a draft of the article by Dr Gordon Anthony. Remaining errors are, though, mine alone. I also wish to acknowledge more general indebtedness to Pr
[normal]ofessor Desmond Greer, who was a wise and steady counsellor during my earlier employment at Queen’s University from 1979 to 1991. I fear this article will not meet Des’s high standards of scholarly rigour, which are legendary, but it is nonetheless dedicat
[normal]ed to him with admiration and affection.
