[normal] Cf 
[normal]Secretary of State for the Home Department v MB
[normal] (12 April 2006), where 
[normal]Sullivan J held that 
[normal]s. 3(10) of the Prevention of Terrorism Act 2005
[normal] did not give the respondent the fair hearing he was entitled to under the Human Rights Act 1998 because (in the judge’s view) it confined the court to looking only at the one-sid
[normal]ed material available to the Secretary of State 
[normal]at the time the order was made
[normal]. The judge said that the thin veneer of legality which was sought to be applied by 
[normal]s 3 of the 2005 Act
[normal] could not disguise the reality that the Convention rights of people subjected to control orders were being determined not by an independent court but by executive decision-making untrammelled by any prospect of effective judicial
[normal] supervision. As it was not possible for the court to conclude that the Secretary of State’s decisions were legally flawed upon the basis of the one-sided information then available to him, the control order had to continue in force but s. 3(10) was declar
[normal]ed to be incompatible with Convention rights.
