[normal] S. 172(1) of the Constitution of South Africa 1996 (formerly s. 98(5) of the Interim Constitution 1994): ‘When deciding a constitutional matter within its power, a court (a) must declare that any law or conduct that is inconsistent with the Constitution 
[normal]is invalid to the extent of its inconsistency; and (b) may make any order that is just and equitable, including (i)
[normal]&#xad;
[normal] an order limiting the retrospective effect of the declaration of invalidity; and (ii) an order suspending the declaration of invalidity for
[normal] any period and on any conditions, to allow the competent authority to correct the defect’. The power to suspend a declaration of invalidity was first exercised in 
[normal]S v Ntuli
[normal] 1996 (1) S.A.L.R. 1207, where the government was given some 16 months to produce c
[normal]orrective legislation. This deadline was later extended but ultimately the Constitutional Court held that the Minister’s officials had failed to act promptly and diligently and that the order of invalidity must therefore stand: 
[normal]Minister of Justice v Ntuli
[normal] 
[normal](5 June 1997).
